          </widget>
         </item>
         <item>
          <widget class="QLabel" name="description_labell">
           <property name="layoutDirection">
            <enum>Qt::LayoutDirection::LeftToRight</enum>
           </property>
           <property name="autoFillBackground">
            <bool>false</bool>
           </property>
           <property name="frameShape">
            <enum>QFrame::Shape::NoFrame</enum>
           </property>
           <property name="text">
            <string>Nutrigenomics sits at the intersection of two fields that have each seen rapid progress
over the last two decades: high-throughput genomics and computational data sci-
ence. The promise is straightforward—if we know which genetic variants a patient
carries, and if we know how those variants relate to nutritional metabolism, we can
offer dietary guidance that goes beyond generic population-level recommendations.
The challenge, as with most things in bioinformatics, is that the data is messy, het-
erogeneous, and far too large to interpret by hand.
This thesis describes a computational framework that attempts to close part of
that gap. The system takes a patient’s raw genotype data—a list of Single Nucleotide
Polymorphisms (SNPs) extracted from a genotyping panel—and maps it against the
GRPM-GWAS nutrigenetic dataset [DFMP+25] to produce personalised risk assess-
ments for nutrition-related diseases. Beyond simple allele matching, the framework
incorporates machine learning models trained on BERT-encoded features to classify
the significance of each genetic variant.</string>
           </property>
           <property name="textFormat">
            <enum>Qt::TextFormat::PlainText</enum>
           </property>
